In .NET 10 (targeting Android API 35+), `AdjustResize` is fully deprecated because Android now enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering. The replacement is responding to **window insets** for the IME (keyboard).

Here's the modern approach:

## Option 1 — Handle IME insets in your Android platform code

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    // Edge-to-edge is now the default in API 35+
    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var systemBars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());

        v.SetPadding(
            systemBars.Left,
            systemBars.Top,
            systemBars.Right,
            Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, systemBars.Bottom));

        return insets;
    }
}
```

## Option 2 — Use MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`

MAUI has a built-in scroll-into-view behavior. Ensure it's **not** disabled:

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs — do NOT add this line (it disables auto-scroll):
// .ConfigureMauiHandlers(h => KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect());
```

This works for `Entry`/`Editor` controls inside a `ScrollView`, but for a pinned bottom bar, Option 1 is more reliable.

## Recommended layout structure

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" />
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

With the insets listener above, the bottom padding adjusts dynamically when the keyboard opens, pushing your input bar up.

**Key takeaway:** Replace the old `SoftInputMode` call with a `WindowInsetsCompat` listener that applies the IME bottom inset as padding.
